\par \tab \tab MR. WHITMORE:  You can also get some handle on accuracy if you have some data that's known for both respondents and nonrespondents.  If there's any information from the sampling frame or whatever that you know from respondents and nonrespondents so that you can compare them, that can give you actually direct ways of estimating bias, and it's particularly applicable when you are looking at item nonresponse as opposed to the unit nonresponse of the individual firms that you are surveying.
\par \tab \tab So that if you are looking at item nonresponse rates, you might also want to look at estimating nonresponse bias based on data that you have for other items, particularly for items that are getting low response rates.
\par \tab \tab So in addition to looking at response rates themselves, if there is anything you can do to directly address the nonresponse bias, that would be a useful addition.
\par \tab \tab MR. BROENE:  Okay.  Thank you.
\par \tab \tab MS. HUTZLER:  I'd like to go back to Nicholas' issue about the timeliness versus accuracy.  It's clear that our users want timeliness.  The quicker we can get it out, the better.
\par \tab \tab MR. BURTON:  Yes, but you don't want crap either.
\par \tab \tab MS. HUTZLER:  That's right.  So what I'd like to ask you is what error do you think would be reasonable in terms of that tradeoff?  I mean, if we are trying to deal with timeliness, how close to the actual estimate do you think we need to be when we put out that data?
\par \tab \tab MR. HENGARTNER:  I tried to ask that question over lunch.  
\par \tab \tab MR. BERNSTEIN:  It just depends on what we are talking about here.
\par \tab \tab MR. BURTON:  His answer is going to be different than mine.
\par \tab \tab MS. HUTZLER:  Well, good.  Let's hear them all.  WE have the time.
\par \tab \tab MR. BURTON:  No, I mean, just a numerical -- There isn't --
\par \tab \tab MR. BERNSTEIN:  It depends on both, which data we're talking about, and it also -- You know, it's also maybe not just the question of how fast and how accurate.  Let's take the natural gas issue we were talking about earlier.  
